o, Milwaukee and St. Paul\nRailroad has applied to the Wisconsin\nState Railroad Commission for authoril)\nto issue KO.O.O.OD) bonds.\nHoward Elliott says: \"Funds' for meet\ning Boston and Maine's J10.000.0JO ma\nturity In February hae not yet been\nraised, and up to the present time the\ndirectors do not know where they are\ncoming from.\"\nJ P Morgan Co the First National\nBank, and the National City Bank are\noffering $2,945,000 41-2 per cent gold New\nYork Central line equipment trust certifi\ncates of 1913 at a price to net approx\nimately 613 per cent.\nThe year that Is to nearly at Its close\nhas been a notable one In many respects\nwith respect to the outside securities\nmarket. Most of the companies whose\nshares arc traded In on the Curb have\nenjoyed genuine prosperity. Many of\nthem are rounding out the best years of\ntheir history. This Is particularly true\nIn the Standard Oil group. The consump\ntion of petroleum products, according to\nan official of one of the larger concerns,\nbus increased approximately 59 per cent\nin recent ears and Is expected to show\nan equally large adancc during the next\ntn clvenior.th or so\nClose students of the affairs of the\nUnited Cigar Stores Company aro con\nfidently looking forward to the declara\ntion of an extra dividend of generous\nproportions at the forthcoming meeting\nof the directors, which Is scheduled for\nilio sixth of next month. Good opinion\nis that the regular disbursement of 1 1-4\nper cent will bo posted and an extra of\nlike amount. It is also quite generally\nbelieved that tha regular rate of divi\ndends will be Increases to at least 7 per\ncent and, perhaps, 8 per cent annually.\nNot a little interest is centered In the\nmeeting referred to, as it Is expected that\nthen, or immediately thereafter, some an\nnouncement will be made as to the plans\nnow formulating; for the application of\nUnited Cigar Stores selling methods in\nthe conduct of tho Hiker liegeman\nDrug Co., control of which was recently\nacquired by Interests also tn control of\nthe Cigar Stores.\nS. B Cliapin to TV. B. HIbbs The re\nactionary tendency the marker displayed\nwas due to the pressure of profit-taking\nsales by local operators, who were most\nactive la starting the market up In the\nbull movement, which developed a fort\nnight ago.\nWhat Impressed most of the tradlnjr\nclement was the continued heavy selling\nat intervals ay some of the brokers who\nusually liandlo the orders for two of the\nlargest local outside operators. This sell\nIBS WWt most pronounctd In .Readlnc; and\nUnited States Steel, but. was scattered\nthroughout the list.\nThe market has been merely In a trad\ning- position for a turn bn the bull side.\nConsequently the outburst of profit-taking\nwas a perfectly natural development of\nwhat was to have been expected tn even\ning up over the year-end settlements.\nThe lack of foundation to any of the bull\nrumors regarding the dissolution of the\nsuits against the Steel Corporation, Amer\nican Can, or the anthracite coal trust Is\nlikely to cause a further reaction In\nprices, after which the market will prob\nably develop a fresh upturn.\nHarrlman Co. About 10.000.000 pounds\nof copper were sold vVsterday morning\nto foreign and domestic consumers at l\ncents a pound. The United Metals Sell\ning Company has sold fully two months'\noutput of the companies for which It\nacts as agent. During the last twenty\ndays It Is estimated that fully SO per cent\nof the buying of the metal has been for\nforelsn account On the other hand, do\nmestic consumers have scarcely started\nto buy, and will require a considerable\namount of copper for February and\nMarch delivery.\nN. L. Carpenter Co. Stocks are in\nclined to sag on account of the foreign\nliquidation In Canadian Pacific. TVs\ndon't look for any decline of conse\nquence and are of the opinion that cer\ntain Issues should be accumulated on any\nrecession. We believe that the con\nstructive policy of the present adminis\ntration, combined with the new cur\nrency bill gradually will restore confi\ndence and cause a. better demand for se\ncurities and an upward trend in prices.\nLewis Johnson Co. The market\nshows reactionary again as Ixindon and\nthe Continent have been luite heay\nsellers on the rise and naturally there 't\nsome profit-taking here on substantial\nimprovement in prices which took place\nlast week. Possibly the retarding Influ\nence also has been the action of the\nInterstate Commerce Commission In call\ning for an answer from the railroad tc\na large number of further questions. It\nalso docs not look as If the banking in\nterests were jet favorably Inclined to a\nbull market. When we look back, how\naviv, to conditions last June, there has\nbeen a wonderful Improvement In the\ngeneral situation and this ultimately\nshould affect sentiment.\nNEW YORK PRODUCE\nNew iotk lite. 29-StlLLFEED-Flrm; nulet\ndralinci. Srsios bran, in ldpound sacks, 25.30.\nstandard nillins. 2S.50 Western red doc. 29 30; win\ntrr wheat in 103-pound sacks, to amrc. 27 00, city\nIran, iu bulk, 21 40, Argentine lean, to arrire. nornl\nRTB fLOUIt-Stredy inrrrrirr Is lifeless. Good\ntc clicire, 3 Xb3 SI\nCO UN MEAL-Flat business is slow Klln-dned\nfor extort. 3.03 ci arss rata!, in ba;. 1 4al 60.\nBICKttHBAT FLOl It-Dull, but price firm;\nsi rvlirs m small. Choice Quoted at !CCs3.2S per 103\npounds,\nIIAY-Reerirts III tons thoice sells moderately;\nlow trades .low No 1 timothy. l.OoalOPj, standard,\nLOCwICS No 2, 9S No 3 eta53.\nSTRAW -Urrcirta, 30 Ions, steady. Inquiry Is dulL\nLong ne quoted at S390r-\nP))KK steady small dealing. Mess. 23.01U2S73;\nfsmily 23 0Cs27 0C clrar. 200Os2200.\nBrKF-Mrsdy Inquiry l mnr Packet, l'COs\nII Oil family. 19COS30.CO\nI. Villi Weaker limited bu.ines\". Prune Western\n11 CO refined etsitinrnl. 1IJ0, rw.th American 11 91\nrrflned Braiilian in kri. I2.W) Ixef strsrlne, S\nssked lsrd strsrlne dull New otk, IPs\nBOSTON COPPERS.\nI urnnbed hf W I! Hlbbs i Co\nUv.ntiire