eather would justify taking a street\ncar Those who have ever used gas,\nelectricity and electric power cannot\nchange their mode of living and business\noperations by returning to oil lamps,\ncandles and coat Statistics of tho past\ndecade show that street railways, gas\nand elertrie light companies have In\ncreased In their gross earnings in greater\nproportion than the normal increase in\npopulation in communities which they\nserve.\nWhen business is poor less goods are\ncarried and fewer people ride in rail\nroads, but probobly the same amount\nof water, electricity and gas is consum\ned, and probably as manv people ride\nin street cars\nC0AI DEALERS TO COMBINE.\nnalllniorr Concern; Mnr Participate\nIn Slllllon-dollar Slrrerr.\nTho Baltimore coal trade is watching\nwith keen interest the formulation ot\nplans for one of tho largest and most\nImportant moves that has ever affected\nretail dealers In anthracite coal in this\ncity the consolidation of a score or more\nof the larger firms dealing in that com\nmodity.\nThe successful working of the plan In\nNew York. Philadelphia and elsewhere\nAttracted -the attention of men who\nknew the situation In Baltimore, and\narmed with assurances ot the liberal\nsupport ot capital they worked out the\nplan to bring under one big concern\ntwenty or so of the larger retail firms\ndealing In anthracite coal. The trans\nactions as planned will Involve mo-v\nthan a million dollars. Between fifty\nand sixty coabards and waterfront\nproperties owned by twenty or more\nfirms would be transferred to\" the combi\nnation. If all approached agree to enter.\nIt is said.\nBALTIMORE MELON CUT.\nTTercnntHe Trnst nnil Deposit Com\nlnn Declares lllvlileml.\nThe board of directors of the Mercan\ntile Trust and Deposit Company, of\nBaltimore, yesterday at a special meet\ning declared the regular semi-annual\ndividend of 6 per cent and an extra divi\ndend of per? cent, making 3 per cent\nextra for the year.. In addition to 12 per\n5pnt regular,